           owl:equivalentClass <http://purl.org/linguistics/gold/MoodProperty> ;
           rdfs:subClassOf mmoon:LinguisticCategory ;
           mmoon:definition """Mood is an inflectional category expressing modality. [Christian Lehmann, under \"mood\" at http://linguistik.uni-regensburg.de:8080/lido/Lido]

Modalitiy is a functional domain comprising a set of sentence-level semantic categories which have it in common that they specify a condition of or an attitude towards the realization of what is designated by the sentence. [Christian Lehmann, under \"modality\" at http://linguistik.uni-regensburg.de:8080/lido/Lido]"""@en ;
           mmoon:externalDefinition <http://purl.org/olia/olia.owl#Moodfeature> ;
           rdfs:label "Mood"@en .


###  http://mmoon.org/core/Morph
mmoon:Morph rdf:type owl:Class ;
            mmoon:definition "A morph is a concrete realization of a single morpheme which usually results from segmentation."@en ;
            mmoon:usageNote "A morph resource describes only the perceptible side of a morpheme, i.e. the significans. As such it is not directly associated with a meaning but with a corresponding morpheme resource. The mmoon core vocabulary, however, allows statements such as :Morph :hasMeaning :Meaning in case Morpheme resources are not yet documented."@en ;
            rdfs:label "Morph"@en .


###  http://mmoon.org/core/Morpheme
mmoon:Morpheme rdf:type owl:Class ;
               mmoon:definition """The morpheme class contains the smallest meaning-bearing units of a language. These comprise all semantically or grammatically distinct parts which are identifiable by segmentation of  the morphs of which a word or a word-form consists.

Depending on the kind of correspondence between a morpheme and its morph realization, three kinds of morphemes are established: 1) atomic morphemes, 2) fusional morphemes and 3) empty morphemes."""@en ;
               mmoon:usageNote """A morpheme resource describes only the conceptual side, i.e. the significatum, which is realized by one or more morphs in a certain language. Thus, the meaning(s) it conveys must be always stated via the mmoon:hasMeaning property.

For convenience the morpheme instances are rendered by the same notational means as the morphemic glosses, i.e. a plural morpheme can be rendered in short as \"lang_inv:AtomicMorpheme_PL\"."""@en ;
               rdfs:label "Morpheme"@en .


###  http://mmoon.org/core/MorphemeInventory
mmoon:MorphemeInventory rdf:type owl:Class ;
                        mmoon:definition "The morpheme inventory is the object that contains morphemic entries. It is specified for the natural language it describes."@en ;
                        rdfs:label "Morpheme Inventory"@en .


###  http://mmoon.org/core/MorphemicGloss
mmoon:MorphemicGloss rdf:type owl:Class ;
                     mmoon:definition "The gloss is the abstract identity of a morpheme and/or a meaning. It serves as a metalinguistic representation of (mostly morphological) meanings."@en ;
                     mmoon:usageNote "Most of the glosses used for grammatical concepts are taken from the Leipzig Glossing Rules  (https://www.eva.mpg.de/lingua/pdf/LGR08.02.05.pdf) or from Lehmann 2004 (http://christianlehmann.eu/publ/img.pdf). Lexical senses are usually glossed in English by using the orthographic representation of the lexical element (such as stems and roots) but can be also given in the language of the MMoOn morpheme inventory."@en ;
                     rdfs:label "Morphemic Gloss"@en .


###  http://mmoon.org/core/MorphologicalRelationship
